edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e: what did you think about my fullscreen suggestion for a fullscreen element stack? I don't think they thought through the implications the nested case is not some complex edge case that most apps can't hit. You can hit it as soon as you can make a document full-screen that contains some other content that supports full-screen, which could easily happen by accident even as soon as you have a document that supports full-screen that might contain an embedded Youtube video, for example I'll follow up to that thread ok that seems broken we can at least make the simple things work actually it will "Esc" has to always bust out of all fullscreening I'm not sure what the current behavior is, but I think it needs to break out well, that can be up to the UA if the UA is permanently in fullscreen mode then I don't think "press ESC to exit fullscreen" would ever be the right message to display

I suggested that in http://lists.whatwg.org/htdig.cgi/whatwg-whatwg.org/2011-October/033549.html but responses were not enthusiastic Please only talk about making elements fullscreen though We're not really making documents fullscreen One alternative is making requestFullscreen always do its thing and exitFullscreen always do a full exit Yeah, though given the number of different scenarios I think the user will always find it confusing :( If the user is already fullscreen for instance (by using F11) and then gets the message that "Esc" will get him/her out but it will actually not... Gecko will exit browser fullscreen if element fullscreen is quit? I doubt users will like that... It's not how browser fullscreen and YouTube behave today If I use fullscreen mode on Mac OS I don't want the browser to just exit that after I have watched a video

f139aba52f9fa1394b4034a7954b2220: I will ask weinig or somebody to tae a look f139aba52f9fa1394b4034a7954b2220: we have our own regression tests for querySelector but I doubt they are very powerful we specifically didn't want to try to make tests for every possible kind of selector including edge cases, though come to think of it that would be more convenient than the tests with red and green boxes usually used for this kind of thing f139aba52f9fa1394b4034a7954b2220: we have a good test framework for tests that purely involve scripting APIs and not layout basically you just write a series of assertions in a JS file like this: shouldBe("Math.abs(1)", "1"); shouldBe("Math.abs(-1)", "1"); and we have some JS files that implement the functions ours is real easy to use and gives pretty results f139aba52f9fa1394b4034a7954b2220: I'll mail you an example (unless you have a WebKit checkout handy in which case I could point you to it) ab7faae5d7b250ea8606486575f8f79c: we group tests in files, all it takes to "run" such a suite is to open the html file in any browser for fully automated execution we have a headless tool that loads all the html files in sequence f139aba52f9fa1394b4034a7954b2220: sent f139aba52f9fa1394b4034a7954b2220: the three files starting with js- are the framework elements-not-in-document.js is the substance of the test case I might also have a script lying around to generate the wrapper HTML files for the script files (they just include the test script plus the CSS file and two helpers) but it's pretty trivial makes good looking output though where it is easy to spot the failures and why they fail in addition to the basic shouldBe tests there's also shouldBeTrue, shouldBeFalse, shouldBeNaN, shouldBeNull, shouldBeUndefined and shouldThrow

Hmm. In the execCommand() use-case, is there really any notable difference between <div align=right> and <div style="text-align: right">? The only obvious differences I can think of involve things like fixed-width block descendants, which you can't really get in a normal contenteditable setup. There's no way to make those with execCommand() either, actually, that I've seen.  Although you'd think there should be. Seems like a pretty obvious feature to add. I guess I'll spec it as text-align across the board for now, and change it if any problems arise.

467f6d43402c6573237052cefcc252db: It doesn't leak if you make createElementNS lowercase and throw upon importing non-lowercase node from an XML doc 467f6d43402c6573237052cefcc252db: but I'm not convinced that plugging the leak is worthwhile 467f6d43402c6573237052cefcc252db: do you mean implementation strategy? 467f6d43402c6573237052cefcc252db: the alternative is that each element node has a pointer to an interned compound name struct (aka. node info in Gecko and qualified name in WebKit) and this struct has pointers to four interned items: namespace, local name, prefix and ASCII-lowercased local name then in XML, selectors preserve case and match against local name and in HTML selectors are lower-case and match against ASCII-lowercased local name making SVG-in-text/html nodes give the appearance of case-insensitive selector matching and the third alternative is using a single local name atoms on both sides and magic fixup lists that can't support textArea 467f6d43402c6573237052cefcc252db: different results so, yeah I guess there's no way around the spec forcing which side you put the dual atoms on 467f6d43402c6573237052cefcc252db: yesterday I didn't know that bz would be OK with HTMLness compare plus pointer compare instead of just pointer compare :-)

I used a non-boolean data attribute some time ago, with a list of things somewhat like <a title="text for a tooltip/popup message" _formatted="alternative HTML-formatted text" onmouseover="scripted_tooltip_window(this)">Short uninteresting link text</a>, so it would have sensible non-JS (and non-CSS) fallback but the script could make use of more interesting data to display in its non-standard tooltip-like-thing, without having to store all that data a ... a long way away (I can probably think of better non-nonstandard ways of doing that now, but they'd seem more convoluted than just sticking an extra attribute on the element, and I couldn't think of anything better back then) If there's only one script data attribute, perhaps people would start doing <textarea scriptdata="maxlength=300"> (which is much clearer than scriptdata="300") or <textarea scriptdata='{"maxlength":300,"minlength":100}'>, and make their own custom parsers, which seems kind of pointless when you've already got an HTML parser that could do all the work for you I think I have a mild natural distaste for using $ but that's probably just because I'm too used to Perl and code like |print qq{<foo \$data="$data">}| is not especially beautiful, which isn't a particularly valid concern... Are people trying to make HTML5 and XHTML5 as equivalently powerful as possible, and trying to minimise the exceptions like <p><ul/></p>? (If so, presumably that would rule out $ (if it's not allowed in XML) and : (if it'd mean you couldn't do a lossless HTML5->XHTML5 conversion of <div foo:bar=x>))

IE supports SVG with a plugin. hax: JSON is basically just a text representation of javascript objects. It's nice and human readable and very easy for js to parse, so it's a good way of passing data between the server and javascript e.g. if your server side scripting has a JSON parser you can basically say 'here's an object. Turn it into JSON.' and plonk it straight onto the page for the javascript to deal with. (It's slightly more complicated than that, but that's the idea) hax: Right hax: If you want your javascript to parse a string in JSON format then you do, but if you're just including it on the page server side before the page gets loaded then you don't. (The most common instance of the former is if you use an XHR to get the JSON string) There's a small js library for the object -> string conversion if you need it. But the other direction is just a straightforward eval See http://www.json.org/ for more information. hax: It's a pretty convenient format to send json from js to the server. hrm. does anyone know if there's a way to provide explicit branch prediction hints to sunpro (a la __builtin_expect in gcc)? i haven't found anything relevant in the docs... jmcp: this is code that's not necessarily safe to pass aggressive optimization flags to the evil otherwise known as openafs ;) well, i can't easily convince customers to recompile several times with profiling feedback, and non-profiling driven branch prediction heuristics sometimes work well, and sometimes don't... paul: that's the big issue is keeping error handling paths out of the main instruction stream, which explicit hinting to the compiler helps you do http://pastebin.ca/163303 the compiler's "smarts" are still fundamentally a heuristic. if I explicitly know that a particular code path will almost never be taken, i think there should be a way of notating that in the source. whether or not the compiler chooses to honor that notation is beyond my control. jmcp: then i'm not doing my due diligence with a profiler. i'm not sure how the fact that i could adversely affect performance by being an idiot programmer negates the usefulness of notational primitives to improve performance in the hands of a good coder jmcp: i mostly agree with you. the linux kernel uses the explicit hinting primitives too much, imho but i do think they can be helpful when used judiciously paul: i definitely agree with that yep. i've played around with that before. it seems to do a nice job. the issue is in my particular case it's an oss distributed filesystem where most organizations recompile with specific autoconf flags. it's going to be rather tough to convince them to rebuild several times with profiling feedback paul: unfortunately, this is a huge dev project i'm being paid to work on, and the contract doesn't let me release any of the code until it's done right. multiple RW replica support is still a good 18-24 months off gpfs does linux AND aix :p hahaha i really need to buy a usiii machine so i can pass -h to collect :) the tracing framework on aix is a very different beast

Meriwether: Well, there's evim which does that as well. Cream is basically evim with a bunch of stuff added. Any time a command can take a motion you simply hit the key for the command then a motion that would normally move the cursor and vim applies the command to the the area of the file that covers the current cursor position to where the motion would take the cursor. Some command keys can be "doubled" so the motion is the current line. So, for example, "dd" deletes the current line but you can do "dj" to delete the current and next line. Or "dG" deletes from the current line to the end of the file. == reindents the current line... So if you want to reindent the full file you need to type: gg=G gg moves to the top of the file, and =G formats from the current line to the bottom. It's very important to understand how to use commands that use a motion "argument". Commands that take a motion can also take what's called a "text-object" as their motion. ...Which can often affect an area surrounding the cursor--both before and after its current position. People often use visual mode when they don't need to because they don't understand how to use command-motion groups. I think most people who rely on visual mode need to go through the vimtutor again. f00li5h: You can also precede almost any command with a count.

69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: I'm not sure what you find hard to understand about the appcache use-case in https://www.w3.org/Bugs/Public/show_bug.cgi?id=14702 The desired behavior is basically: (1) If you're online, proceed as normal.  Fetch everything from online or the HTTP cache as appropriate, and update appcached resources as appropriate. (2) If you're offline, use the appcache. And that's it. This is desirable over http caching because (1) http cache doesn't reliably work offline, and (2) http cache entries can disappear non-atomically, creating a broken app. Whereas the appcache for a site expires all at once, so it's easy to tell why the page is "broken", since it doesn't work offline at all. You even allude to precisely the benefit being sought ("other than making the file available offline") in comment #24, but don't seem to understand that's all that's desired. Because it's a *very significant* restructuring. And it's not all rainbows and sunshine.  Sending an empty <body> and filling it with script is bad for spiders and accessibility generally. I don't know what the effects of filling in the body from script are to common a11y tools.

Which part of charsUntil is slow? like, is it doing lots of complex calculation itself, or is it just spending its time pulling characters out of Python data structures? Try removing all the functionality from the function and see how that affects performance :-) and if it's still just as slow, then it must be the interface with surrounding code that's slow, in which case I guess you can't do much to optimise that function by itself You could remove all the stuff that implements the "until" thing, and run it with test data that doesn't depend on the "until" thing working, and see how much effect that has Seems like charsUntil can be made ~30% faster just by using a list instead of a deque (and storing the string reversed, so all the operations happen on the tail of the list) (except for readChunk but that can be made to only be called when the list is nearly empty, I think) (Also it could maybe be made much faster by storing a list of strings, instead of a list of characters) might look at that later tonight a11aabeeceeae6b8cb5d12ea06b56554: Which "that" do you mean? f139aba52f9fa1394b4034a7954b2220: Doesn't all office software have autosave? a11aabeeceeae6b8cb5d12ea06b56554: It'd let you run regexps and depending on how Python stores lists, it might be hugely more memory-efficient (hence cache-efficient and everything) wishes Opera didn't insist on opening patch files with "less" a11aabeeceeae6b8cb5d12ea06b56554: It'd let you run regexps without wasting loads of time calling 'join' (and without wasting memory etc) a924fb58d2c25874322f4e5126f608b9: I never did, since that'd be stupid :-) b07211a0c7cb119232799d2119cea90f: Yes a11aabeeceeae6b8cb5d12ea06b56554: I can't see any references other than a dozen mentions of self.queue in inputstream.py, and it should be feasible to optimise things somewhat without changing its interface discovers that the bottleneck in his code is "for i in range(self.chunkOffset, len(self.chunk)):", so he rewrites it as an ugly "i = ...; while i < ...; ...; i += 1" and cuts 40% off his execution time (I would have thought Python wouldn't be so incredibly dumb as to fail to optimise that very common case) The whole point of this code is that lists are slow and I want to avoid them :-p fd9ef1223e855714294498ebfde79f98: Aha, thanks, that's not noticeably slower than the manual loop, which is nice :-) (though it'd still be nicer if Python did that optimisation automatically) f139aba52f9fa1394b4034a7954b2220: Canvex is about the only significant <canvas> thing I've done f139aba52f9fa1394b4034a7954b2220: There's http://www.p01.org/releases/DHTML_contests/files/20lines_twinkle/ which might be interesting f139aba52f9fa1394b4034a7954b2220: Also http://glimr.rubyforge.org/cake/canvas.html with various stuff f139aba52f9fa1394b4034a7954b2220: What edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e said :-) f139aba52f9fa1394b4034a7954b2220: Oh, I misinterpreted you in the same way f139aba52f9fa1394b4034a7954b2220: http://canvex.lazyilluminati.com/83/83.zip is an almost recent copy of hopefully all the necessary files (I think it's just missing the Safari logo in the outdoors bit, because the game didn't work in Safari back then) f139aba52f9fa1394b4034a7954b2220: That's because Firefox is stupid, I think Either run it on a local web server, or modify play.xhtml to refer to .svg instead of .svgz ...and if the .zip doesn't include .svg files then gzip -d the .svgz ones gzip-compressed SVG Might need to make sure the web server is configured to send the right content-type/encoding for .svgz - I'm not sure if they do it by default (The problem with using file:/// is that Firefox guesses the content-type but not -encoding for .svgz files, so it tries parsing the compressed data as XML) AddEncoding gzip .svgz f139aba52f9fa1394b4034a7954b2220: It shows the framerate, and I overrode your new tab command because I'm cruel and unthoughtful

User agents, such as web crawlers, do have interest in semantics. It would be nice to specify title and behaviour using CSS. For the time being, behaviour relies on JavaScript and it can be applied via JavaScript, although this is a bit inefficient. There is no workaround for title. (where no script is available, that is). However, managing hyperlinks in the same way would be insane. Images and hiding are subject to CSS. Ordinarily, there should be just one element called "edit". Or no such elements, of course. I can see nothing wrong in having to change the stylesheet. CSS is modular because of @import. The only problem with CSS is that you cannot explicitly inherit style from a structurally unrelated class. That problem clearly wants a solution but it is not a problem in HTML.
